### **Strategy & Scope**

### Project Brief: Mental Health Awareness

External User’s Goal:  
The user seeks accessible, beginner-friendly information on mental health, including how to recognize common issues and manage stress, presented in a supportive and organised layout.

Site Owner’s Goal:  
The site owner wants to create a welcoming webpage that provides basic mental health information using a clean and supportive design. The focus is on using HTML and CSS with Bootstrap to create a calming and well-organised user experience.

Potential Features might Include:

* Hero Section with Positive Messaging: A Bootstrap Jumbotron with an encouraging message about mental health, using a calming colour scheme and a simple background image.  
* Information Cards: Use Bootstrap’s card components to present mental health tips and common issues, providing a visually appealing way to organise content.  
* Resource Links: A grid layout for external links to mental health resources, styled with Bootstrap buttons to make them stand out.  
* Positive Affirmations: Use Bootstrap’s text utilities to include a section with uplifting quotes or messages to encourage users.

Project overview:

This site will be used as an intermediate signposting and mental health first-aid resource for people with Autism and ADHD, for whom typical mental health first aid advice is not always effective. 

The home page will aim to direct in four key user types. 

1\. A neurodivergent looking for general mental health and wellness information and advice, 

2.An employer looking for advice about ND. 

3\. A ND experiencing poor mental health, requiring mental health first aid and advice, and 

4\. A ND experiencing a mental health crisis, requiring urgent help.

The information architecture will be a hub+ spoke type with a Navbar that provides dropdown for each category.

![][image1]The homepage will be the landing page from which each user type can navigate to their required info in a quiz style set of buttons. This style seeks to put the user at ease due to a predictable and structured user experience. With soft fade transitions and muted colors to not overwhelm the audience. 

**Structure \+ skeleton**

Clear, Clean layout. Hero image will be Simple illustration, perhaps some overlaid text of a positive, encouraging nature.

**Surface:**

Color:

Below is the color scheme generated using Coolors.io, it is intended to be easy to look at and calming. Dark color to provide contrast where needed, Colors are clear in each color blindness simulator, except Achromatopsia (palette below). For this reason, the Orange, Sage  and lavender shades will never be used against one another, for example as background and text color.

#### Font: Open sans, Arial, Sans-serif

#### Special consideration needs to be made here because of the high likelihood that users may have language processing or learning difficulties. For this reason we will use a sans-serif font with high legibility, slightly increased letter spacing and medium weight. We will avoid capitalisation, all-caps and italic writing to improve predictability and legibility for those with dyslexia or similar reading difficulty.

#### We will also need to pay particular attention to our accessible design elements.

We have used the following advice to help in our decision-making here: (Can be found at: [https://www.bdadyslexia.org.uk/advice/employers/creating-a-dyslexia-friendly-workplace/dyslexia-friendly-style-guide](https://www.bdadyslexia.org.uk/advice/employers/creating-a-dyslexia-friendly-workplace/dyslexia-friendly-style-guide) )

## **Readable fonts**

* Use sans serif fonts, such as Arial and Comic Sans, as letters can appear less crowded. Alternatives include Verdana, Tahoma, Century Gothic, Trebuchet, Calibri, Open Sans.  
* Font size should be 12-14 point or equivalent (e.g. 1-1.2em / 16-19 px). Some dyslexic readers may request a larger font.  
* Larger inter-letter / character spacing (sometimes called tracking) improves readability, ideally around 35% of the average letter width. If letter spacing is excessive it can reduce readability.  
* Inter-word spacing should be at least 3.5 times the inter-letter spacing.  
* Some dyslexic people find that larger line spacing improves readability. It should be proportional to inter-word spacing; 1.5/150% is preferable.  
* Avoid underlining and italics as this can make the text appear to run together and cause crowding. Use bold for emphasis.  
* Avoid using all capital letters and uppercase letters for continuous text. Lower case letters are easier to read

We will refer to the above resource when we begin CSS styling.  
We will avoid using crowded and semi-transparent backgrounds for text blocks and stick to single-color backgrounds(Not white) with high contrast text color (Not black)

We will left-align text where possible and avoid using Justify.  
If there is time, we will provide various font modification options to users on articles for different user needs (Font size, letter spacing, **bo**ld **rea**ding **met**hod, line spacing, Dyslexic fonts)

**Layout:**

Wire frames indicate general positioning but the specific styling of the site is influenced heavily by the intended audience. Whose needs vary. The target users experience extremely high baseline cognitive load so design will be as simple and clean as possible, with rounded corners, clear lines, medium weight typeface and suitable colouring. Any Transitions should be kept to a soft and relaxing feel, e.g fade out-in.  
We will use a left-right priority for user stories that will account for cognitive load. I.e. Users we expect to have a high cognitive load (more overwhelmed) at the start point will have their most likely pathways on the top left of the screen layout, allowing them to find them without having to read every option. 

Users in crisis who we expect to have nearly no available cognition, will see “Crisis options highlighted in a shade of red that we will experiment with to strike a balance between visibility and color palette cohesion. The crisis buttons will be spaced out on the home screen, more than one crisis button will be available on each home screen.

“Burdened Brains” brand name will attract visitors who may be in need of mental health advice. This also refers to the fact that Neurodivergent people tend to operate with a higher baseline of unhelpful, distracting cognition. It’s important that we explain on the desktop homepage the messaging behind this… That the things we judge ourselves for, and the comparisons we make which make us feel like we’re not real adults or not cut-out for life can be explained by the fact that we are constantly dealing with a higher burden of information than a neurotypical brain. And that, in fact, our perceived shortcomings are not a reflection of our character, but rather a reflection of the increased burden we deal with. If life is like a marathon, Neurodivergent people see others jog past in their sport gear and waterbottles, carrying nothing, while we are running with a heavy backpack of sensory information, or hyperactive thoughts and have forgotten our water bottles\! Nobody would compare those runners to us because it’s clear that we are facing a significantly different challenge than our competitors\!


**Changes during development:**
During the development process, the plan evolved due to time constraints and creative, strategic and design decisions made as the project took shape.
For example, the original colour scheme was enhanced with an off-white/yellow colour which provided a much more gentle contrast with the dark purple hue. 

Off-white/yellow : #fffccc

The Quiz section, which was intended to keep things simple and straight-forward would need significantly longer workshopping questions and compiling a quiz pathway using javascript, this places that feature outside of the scope of this project. Though, this will remain on the cards, after project delivery.

The quiz homepage was kept on mobile because it acts as an efficient hub from which our user pathways can stem. 

The decision to use a “hub&spoke” information hierarchy should be revisited, if there is time because this model necessitates the creation of several pages(the spokes), which could draw resources away from the creation of the homepage, which is the core focus of this project.
The decision has been made to pause development of the spoke pages due to time-constraints. These pages will appear as intended on mobile but are not yet styled responsively for laptops and larger.
Home page has been re-designed for laptop and larger to give the user access to navigation options on the top and the left of the screen. 
Home page to include aside section containing articles/blogposts because it was looking a bit bare.
Having trouble with Media queries, I think it may be something about bootstrap 5. I will need to spend some time understanding breakpoints and how to set media queries when using BS5. However, due to time constraints, I will skip certain media query styling
(E.g card text font-size)
Certain style elements I had hoped to use for the quiz design require JavaScript to run, this will make the quiz section (and mobile homepage) more basic than intended, though this could still be good for our user stories.
10. Important lesson to remember: Making sections with comments in css stylesheet is NOT a waste of time. Organising this information as I generate it would have saved me quite a few headaches and quite alot of time!
